        <id>800198</id>
      </contributor>
      <comment>1978: [[:Template:dn]] for [[John Glover]] ([[John Glover (actor)]]?) &amp; [[Michael Gross]] ([[Michael Gross (actor)]]?)</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Redirect|Mahagonny|the ''Mahagonny-Songspiel''|Mahagonny-Songspiel}}
'''''Rise and Fall of the City of Mahagonny''''' ({{Lang|de|''Aufstieg und Fall der Stadt Mahagonny''}}) is a political-satirical [[opera]] composed by [[Kurt Weill]] to a German [[libretto]] by [[Bertolt Brecht]]. It was first performed in [[Leipzig]] on 9 March [[1930 in music#Opera|1930]].

==Composition history==
The libretto was mainly written in early 1927 and the music was finished in the spring of 1929, although both text and music were to be partly revised by the authors later. An early by-product, however, was the ''[[Mahagonny-Songspiel]]'', sometimes known as ''Das kleine Mahagonny'', a concert work for voices and small orchestra commissioned by the Deutsche Kammermusik Festival in [[Baden-Baden]] and premiered there on 18 July 1927. The ten numbers, which include the &quot;Alabama Song&quot; and &quot;Benares Song&quot;, were duly incorporated into the full opera. The opera had its premiere in [[Leipzig]] in March 1930 and played in Berlin in December of the following year. The opera was banned by the [[Nazism|Nazis]] in 1933 and did not have a significant production until the 1960s.

Weill's score uses a number of styles, including [[ragtime|rag-time]], [[jazz]] and formal [[counterpoint]], notably in the &quot;[[Alabama Song]]&quot; (covered by multiple artists, notably [[The Doors]] and [[David Bowie]]). The lyrics for the &quot;Alabama Song&quot; and another song, the &quot;Benares Song&quot; are in English (albeit specifically [[Idiosyncrasy|idiosyncratic]] English) and are performed in that language even when the opera is performed in its original (German) language.

==Production history==
It has played in opera houses around the world. Never achieving the popularity of Weill and Brecht's ''[[The Threepenny Opera]],'' ''Mahagonny'' is still considered a work of stature with a haunting score. Herbert Lindenberger in his book ''Opera in History'', for example, views ''Mahagonny'' alongside Schoenberg's ''[[Moses und Aron]]'' as indicative of the two poles of modernist opera.

Following the [[Leipzig]] premiere, the opera was presented in Berlin in December 1931 at the [[Theater am Schiffbauerdamm]] conducted by [[Alexander von Zemlinsky]] with [[Lotte Lenya]] as Jenny, Trude Hesterberg as Begbick, and Harald Paulsen as Jimmy. Another production was presented in January 1934 in [[Copenhagen]] at the Det ny Teater.

Other productions within Europe waited until the end of the [[World War II|Second World War]], some notable ones being in January 1963 in London at [[Sadler's Wells Opera]] conducted by [[Colin Davis]] and in Berlin in September 1977 by the [[Komische Oper Berlin|Komische Oper]].

It was not presented in the United States until 1970, when a short-lived April production at the Phyllis Anderson Theatre off Broadway starred [[Barbara Harris (actress)|Barbara Harris]] as Jenny and Estelle Parsons as Begbick.

A full version was presented at the [[Yale Repertory Theatre]] in New Haven, Connecticut, in 1974, with [[Gilbert Price]] as Jimmy and Stephanie Cotsirilos as Jenny. [[Kurt Kasznar]] played Moses. The libretto was performed in an original translation by [[Michael Feingold]]; the production was directed by [[Alvin Epstein]].

In October of 1978, Yale presented a &quot;chamber version&quot; adapted and directed by Keith Hack, with [[John Glover]]{{dn|date=April 2011}} as Jimmy and [[June Gable]] as Begbick. Mark Lynn-Baker played Fatty; [[Michael Gross]]{{dn|date=April 2011}} was Trinity Moses.

Finally, in November 1979 it debuted at the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in a [[John Dexter]] production conducted by [[James Levine]]. The cast included [[Teresa Stratas]] as Jenny, [[Astrid Varnay]] as Begbick, [[Richard Cassilly]] as Jimmy, [[Cornell MacNeil]] as Moses, [[Ragnar Ulfung]] as Fatty and [[Paul Plishka]] as Joe. In 2010, the Met released it on DVD.

The [[Los Angeles Opera]] presented the opera in September 1989 under conductor [[Kent Nagano]] and with a [[Jonathan Miller]] production. Other notable productions in Europe from the 1980s included the March 1986 presentation by the [[Scottish Opera]] in [[Glasgow]]; a June 1990 production in [[Florence]] by the Maggio musicale fiorentino. In October 1995 and 1997, the [[Paris Opera]] staged by [[Graham Vick]], under the baton of [[Jeffrey Tate]] starring [[Marie McLaughlin]] as Jenny, [[Felicity Palmer]] (1995) and [[Kathryn Harries]] (1997) as Begbick, Kim Begley (1995) and Peter Straka (1997) as Jimmy. The July 1998 [[Salzburg Festival]] production featured [[Catherine Malfitano]] as Jenny, [[Gwyneth Jones (soprano)|Gwyneth Jones]] as Begbick, and [[Jerry Hadley]] as Jimmy.

Productions within the US in the last ten years have included those in November 1998 by the [[Lyric Opera of Chicago]] directed by [[David Alden]]. Catherine Malfitano repeated her role as Jenny, while [[Felicity Palmer]] sang Begbick, and [[Kim Begley]] sang in the role of Jimmy. The Los Angeles Opera's February 2007 production directed by [[John Doyle (director)|John Doyle]] and conducted by [[James Conlon]] included [[Audra McDonald]] as Jenny, [[Patti LuPone]] as Begbick, and [[Anthony Dean Griffey]] as Jimmy. This production was recorded on [[DVD]], and subsequently won the 2009 [[Grammy Award]]s for &quot;Best Classical Album&quot; and &quot;Best Opera Recording.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| title=The 51st Annual Grammy Awards Winners List |url=http://www.grammy.com/grammy_awards/51st_show/list.aspx#30 | accessdate=19 February 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Reference necessary|1=In Ireland, the surname &quot;Mahony&quot; is accented on the first syllable, while in the US, the accent falls on the second syllable; the opera is written reflecting the Irish pronunciation. For this reason the Los Angeles Opera production (in English, not the original German), Mahoney was renamed &quot;Jimmy McIntyre.&quot;|date=April 2010}}

